< Text>
Subway has disappointingly skinny subs nowadays, but not submarinas.

The staff are all quite friendly, and the options are good.

I usually get a Box Lunch Special because I can eat the 4 inch sub before my lunch break is over, and it includes cookies and chips. You can get a drink with it but it costs a bit extra.

Definitely a good pick if you're looking for a good sub place.

They also offer salads and soups, but I have never tried them.< /Text>

Uninsured Cleaning and X-ray $350
Prior to the Covid-19 Pandemic it was $175

But I‚Äôve always paid $175 for a non insured cleaning and X-ray, not a penny more. And I‚Äôve always communicated appointment info with their long time receptionist Candace.

< Review>
This is an amazing "spa atmosphere" type office.  Everyone is treated as though they are super special!  Dr. Darce Slate is the ultimate professional. The dental office is very stressful to me.  I'd rather be at a funeral (which I find extremely  stressful)than go to the dentist.  This office-No stress. Everyone works at putting you at ease.  Candace greets you cheerfully on the phone and when you enter the office.  Alyssa is extremely helpful if you have questions.  Dr. Slate has a peaceful presence which is comforting. He's very thorough with explaining your dental assessment in a manner you can understand. I've had a lot of dental work done in the past:  crowns, bridges, dental implants,etc.  Dr. Slate does all of that and more.  Lastly, my dental hygienist is : amazingly smart, energetic, talented at reducing your stress level ( looking at movies, explaining her cleaning and what is needed as she assesses your mouth.)  If it might hurt, you are warned. I have not cancelled any appointments in approximately 2 years.  This office is great! I am grateful!!  May W.

Today is 9/27/19.  My appt.  was for a dental cleaning.  My hygienist greeted me with a smile and a hug as Ientered the office. There was no waiting!!!  This didn't  allow me time to become more anxious. She is very knowledgeable.   She assessed  my dental health and gave me constructive feedback after cleaning.  Dr. Slate checked my teeth afterwards.  He is a gentle giant.  I was given a bag of freebies and offered an assortment of drinks( non alcoholic of course).  All of the staff members are kind.  If kindness had a sound, you would hear it all around in this office.  I have been to a lot of dentists.  I have had dental surgeries, implants, 2 bridges, braces, and routine dental work for over 50 years. I had implants  when it was considered experimental  surgery.  This just means I had to pay full cost.  I can safely say I have the cost of a house in my mouth!  This dental office and staff remain 5 stars plus.<//Review>

<rate>5</rate>< Text>
If you've never experienced Chipotle, you need to go. Do the classic thing and get a burrito. If you are a vegetarian, the sofritas is really good tasting, and it makes for an exceptional meat substitute. For the carnivores, my favorite is the pork (carnitas). The place can get crowded at rush hour, but they have a very efficient staff, and the line will move quickly. This is not a quiet place to eat. So, if you're looking for a bit more privacy, it's probably best to take it to go.<//Text>

<review>Our group of 4 arrived at 6:45 PM on Saturday night. We were allowed to choose where to sit as there was only 1 other group there. Each of us had eaten there before and returned because both the service and food are good. Sometimes the wait staff seem to hover but that is due to the lack of additional customers.
We each had a different dish and split 2 desserts of Tiramisu. The food portions are generous.
The posted hours show open until 9:00 PM. At 8:20 the owner shut off the lights on the parking lot side of the restaurant and was giving the message they were ready to close. On Saturday night? It seemed a little inhospitable so that is the reason for 4 stars!<//review>< pictures>

<Review>Very dishonest business. I could not fully rest at night until I completed this review for people to see. This gym single handedly ruined my trust in all gyms.

This is an example of their dishonesty (you can mail in a written cancelation to the address listed in the contract under "cancellation" section). However, I would definitely send certified mail and have a notary verify the contents, because I don't trust this business. I also don't think they would actually sign for mail, but I can not prove that (I want to emphasize that I can not prove if they would or would not sign for certified mail).

It appears their money making plan is to basically take advantage of people, because it's cheaper to pay a few hundred bucks to this gym than paying a lawyer approximately $250.00 an hour to represent you in civil court (this gym does use collection agencies). <Text>This is a resort we like to go to, over and again, especially for spring skiing. Everything is so well done, lots of Covid safety rules, enforced by the lift operators. Good grooming keeps enough trails open to make it fun. Base village has reopened so plenty of food choices too. Pass works at Alpine Meadows which is smaller, quieter, very scenic. Worth a day for sure.</Text>< Pictures>

< review>
Our first visit and first time spring skiing as well.  The ski area is great.  The easier slopes higher on the mountain are really good, large and plenty of trails to learn quickly.  The blue slopes are challenging with different terrain in the mix.  I would definitely recommend Squaw/Olympic Valley for Every level of skier.</review>

< Text>
Excellent ski resort close to the Reno Tahoe area. Famous for hosting the olympics many years ago. BEAUTIFUL VIEWS ALL AROUND!!! Great terrain for skiing here, tons of different lifts with dozens of runs all over the mountain. Lift lines are not too bad, but can be long during the busy weekends. Plenty of parking if you get there early in the AM. Lots of very difficult runs when the snow is good. Looking forward to skiing it more this winter season as well as Alpine Meadows just down the road.<//Text>

< Review>
Squaw is a great resort, lots of opportunities for beginners to learn in the beginner slopes or with the classes and for the more experienced skiers there are lots of hard and off trail slopes. There are plenty of restaurants to eat at after the skiing. The biggest issue with squaw is that everything is very expensive, from the tickets to the food, to the houses and rentals.</Review>

< review>
I'm not a skier, but I love to stay here during the summer for hiking. The location is perfect for accessing most Tahoe trails. Prices are much more reasonable during the summer, and especially during the fall. The place is pretty dead in the fall. Most shops are closed, and restaurants are inconsistently open. And, for god sake, shop before you get there. Alice's Grocery is like shopping in Switzerland. Prices are ridiculous. Avoid that place like the plague.< /review>

<Review>There wasn't a ton of snow, but Squaw was still a blast. The runs are super fun and well maintained. There's a wide range of accessibility from easy to super challenging. Also, everyone working there was super friendly, from Ski patrol, to information, to the lift operators. I feel like it's a little confusing to find the entrance from the main ski lot, but if you just keep trekking through the village, you'll find the base. Can't wait to come back when there's fresh snow and I can hit the trees!< /Review>< pictures>

< Text>
One of the best resorts in Tahoe. They do an amazing job with events and the programing in the village. Aaron Tippet the events manager is a top notch human. Love working with him. They have music and fireworks every Saturday. Also Laser tubing. Not to mention the skiing and boarding is world class. Eat at one of the many restaurants in the village, my favorite is the Nectar spot, the wraps are DELICIOUS. Be sure to take a ride in the tram and head up to high camp. While you're there check out the Olympic museum or grab some food.</Text>

This was my first time skiing ever, and¬†luckily I got to ski with my daughter and her friend.

We went to Squaw Valley, one of the best Ski resorts in Tahoe. We were there on March 8, 2020. There was a lot of snow, which made Squaw more charming.

Squaw has plenty of parking and everyone working in squaw so friendly and professional. I was lucky to get Mr. Haz Nabulsi as my¬†ski instructor. He is kind, funny, patient, and loves his job,¬† He made me feel like I‚Äôm with my brother the whole time I was skiing. I did fall a few times but I had a lot of fun. The best feeling was at the end when I took off my ski boots. :)

I love nature, and Mr. Nabulsi showed me all of the mountains on Lake Tahoe and even told me the name of each mountain. I highly recommend him to whoever is new to skiing.¬†Thanks to Mr. Haz Nabulsi.

I plan to come back next year!</Review>

< text>
I am a owner and I stay here throughout the year. In winter they have a lift right from the hotel to the squaw mountain. The squaw mountain is beautiful, and for beginners and advanced use. At night the hotel has the prettiest sunset, in winter and summer. They have amazing activities such as, ice skating, hot tub and pool, and more. In the summer there is a golf course, a pool, crafts for kids, a bar, and much more. The only problem is if you want to get to a lake you have to drive a 15 minute drive there. But, have you ever seen a hotel with a lake and a lift to the mountain? I didn‚Äôt think so. On thing that really made my trip here awesome was the restaurants. They have Sandy‚Äôs Pub, Sweet Potatoes deli, I don‚Äôt know the name but a buffet, Montagna, and the most memorable place Six Peaks. This is so memorable by the sunset right next to you, the beautiful view, delicious food, and just the magical feeling of it. Another thing to add is they have adult and kid shops where you would find Sweet Potatoes. Overall this place is amazing for summer and winter please come her on you next trip to Tahoe< /text>

< Name>
Scott Dukes< /Name>
<Date>1534189492414< /Date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
Great place for summer hiking in Tahoe. If you're looking to take a tram for "high-up" views during the summer, choose Squaw Valley over Heavenly. You can get quality lake views at free lookouts around the lake. You can't get mountain/meadow views like you get at the top of the tram at Squaw.

Last tram returns to the base village at 5:30pm so plan ahead. There's a ton of family friendly hiking at the top, and a small restaurant at the top too (although restaurants at the base village are probably better). Be sure to check out the Olympic museum!</Text>

117099506886887777838</UserId.>
<resp>None</resp>< Name>
Alvin Newman<//Name>
<Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
The resort was excellent, and the rooms very well furnished. We had a two bedroom suite that included a king bed in one room and a full size bed in the second, with a pull out couch in the living room. Living room had beautiful views of the mountain, a very nice fireplace, and a full kitchen.
We were literally steps from the tram going up mountain in the morning, which made skiing and returning to the rooms very easy. There is indoor parking,  an elevator,  two hot tubs in the building, an exercise room, and various firepits spread through the resort.
On the negative side, food at the restaurant was fairly expensive since this is resort so I would recommend taking advantage of the kitchen and preparing at least some meals in. I also rented skis for 3 days, and the rental cost me $150. You may want to consider renting your equipment locally rather than at the resort.
Overall, I had a great time and we'll definitely do it again.<//Review>
<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOYWMbZmALJq0xDd74fAzF_JkcaS2227f4eqNYY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>< time>
1516655565694< /time>

< userid>
102621293108783845054</userid>
<username>Jon< /username>< time>
1513905473494<//time>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
Stayed in a 1 bedroom, 1 den suite. Ended up being a 2 bedroom 2 bath. It was very spacious and comfortable. Since it's in the village, it's just a short walk to the trams up the mountain or to the rentals.

All day Squaw kids were great for our 4, 6, and 8 year old children. They all loved it and got a taste for skiing.

The beginner lessons for us parents were great as well. It was our first time ever and the instructors were very friendly and insightful.</text>

I thought Squaw was great in the summer but it's even better in the winter. It helped that we had over two feet of fresh snow while we were there, but even without that it was a perfect trip. <name>Alex Le</name><Text>Best slopes to enjoy< /Text><Time>1620038876416< /Time><user>117281604405467257167</user>< gmapID>

<UserId.>110310976919153882061</UserId.>< user_name>
Glenn Stewart</user_name>
<Time>1487591744838<//Time>< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< text>
Thankfully I ended up going on a good year. The season in 2017 has been helped significantly by the end of a drought and a lead into significant snow. I met a local who had lived in the area while skiing and he said that it was possibly the best conditions it had been in over 20 years. Two issues come with that. Firstly, I caught a ski bus from San Francisco (NAC) at 4am, which arrived at Truckee at 9am but took a further 2 1/2 hours to reach the resort and another 30 minutes to start skiing. It doesn't help this is the first time skiing in the US, and that comparisons can only be made with Japan (which had world leading transport infrastructure - this type of delay would be unheard of), and Sydney, Australia which still has resorts twice the distance this is from San Francisco, yet I would still have reached the resort earlier. Anyone else coming all this way should stay at the resort. Even Truckee would be a stretch. This early in the morning, all the cars were being turned around. That said, it was a public holiday weekend and possibly expected.
Once skiing though, all was forgiven. The conditions were superb, and lines although long, progressed quickly due to many of the chairs being either high speed or high in seat number. There were a lot of places where I could take in the slopes without anyone else around.
The price though..... you have to be kidding. Another unfortunate result of being able to compare with Japan is that the price of my lift ticket at Squaw would have paid for four days of skiing in Japan, including accomodation, food and hiring of all gear and equipment - with double the annual snowfall. Regardless - still worth of a decent amount of stars. I'll be back!< /text>

<user_id>113589837203961408152< /user_id>< user_name>
Johnny Superhero< /user_name>
< time>
1517305314888<//time>
< Rate>
4</Rate>
< text>
Well, snowboarding is always fun so four stars but I did honestly expect longer runs for somewhere so highly celebrated. This is my first time there when it hasn't been storming and the lifts are actually open though so I haven't seen too much of the mountain yet. Likewise, not much snow this season, not yet, so nothing black was open to ride and powder wasn't an option. As always, I recommend mid-week for shorter lines at the lifts.
Went to the board shop for a stomp pad and they were super helpful and put the pad on for me with the heat gun and everything. Good pricing for what I expect to see at any resort let alone one of this much attraction.
I didn't hit the Irish pub this trip but I highly recommend dropping in for your drink of choice and their loaded tots: awesome, delicious, warm, comfort food perfect for any cold day.
During the summer I hike up there too and it's got plenty o good trails for that and running of course, given it's the start point for the Western States 100, or mountain biking.
The pool there is also a good spot to hang on an off-day from the dirt. The food at the cafe there is pretty good, you can get drinks, and the pool itself is a good layout for chillin out.
If you haven't been yet I also recommend checking out the Olympic museum there; pretty cool stuff in there.<//text>

< text>
Squaw Valley is my favorite playground as a local resident but it is also my fav as a wedding and even portrait photographer. So many backgrounds to choose from and Squaw offers A+ service for planning and venues. You can choose High Camp , the decks, OVL...  all this with village lodging. Worth a visit for sure:)< /text>

< Review>
Loved it, the town is awesome and even though I went during summer and covid times, it is fun to visit, lots of free air, lots of space to distance yourself and just to wake up to lovely weather is awesome. Service was good, only exception is the drain from the shower was clogged, took for ever to drain the water, but the hospitality is great over all, willing to give a second chance? Yes, the cancelation takes about 14 business days to see the money back, that was another negative I noticed, staff is very helpful and understanding. It is not their fault about refund process, staff is 5/5 stars.<//Review>

< text>
What's not to love? This is a huge ski area with plenty of terrain for all skill levels, accessible by a wide variety of lifts from funiculi and aerial tram (which allow descents as well so beginners aren't forced to ski beyond their limits to the base) as well as traditional chairs. Most every one of the staff members were friendly and helpful. There is a mountaintop pool and hot tub (for an added fee) and many other amenities around the village. There is a family of chubby marmots roaming among the peaks for your viewing pleasure. And it's gorgeous.<//text>

<userid>102609323835918155284</userid><name>Matthew</name></record>

<Rating>4</Rating><Gmap_id>0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f</Gmap_id><userid>105936391269677850066</userid><date>1547579538080</date>< review>
Great mountain with one of the best terrain in Tahoe. Plenty to keep busy a skier or snowboarder if any level. Beginner area is mid mountain so even beginners can  get "high". Free parking can get tight on weekends so get there early. Paid parking is free with 3+ people in the car. Facilities are good but food is expensive.< /review>

< review>
Best Tahoe ski resort. Brilliant powder days, terrain for all levels, good food options, great access and parking. There is so much terrain that despite the large number of people that come to squaw, the slopes never feel crowded and lift lines are fairly quick. On both Ikon and Mountain Collective season passes, the 4-pack lift ticket is another economical option.

KT-22 is the best!< /review>

<Name>Taylor Lehman</Name>< time>
1581571140104<//time>
<rate>4</rate>< text>
Squaw valley offers arguably the best skiing in the state of California. Situated in north Lake Tahoe, Squaw stands apart from other local mountains by offering significantly larger acreage, high capacity/high speed chairlifts, typical ski-resort amenities and a variety of events & extracurriculars. Because squaw caters to both local skiers and destination/travel skiers you can expect long lift lines and large crowds at lunch spots and apres. Like many mountains in North America parking and traffic (in & out) of Squaw valley is a bummer. Especially the traffic. Plan your day accordingly and do yourself a favor and stop for a drink or browse the various shops; leaving at 4pm to go to truckee or Tahoe city could easily mean an 1hr+ drive. Squaw offers a lot of varied terrain that will almost certainly satisfy most people. Personally, I‚Äôm a much bigger a fan of alpine meadows (also owned by squaw) but most of my friends would favor Squaw. I will say squaw does seem a little dangerous at times and could use a bit more roping-off and signage for rocks, cliffs, obstructions, etc. This shouldn‚Äôt be too much of a worry since Skiing by definition is a dangerous sport. Lastly, the snow in California is and always will be California snow. Do not expect Rocky Mountain conditions. Obviously some years will be better than others but more often than not, snow isn‚Äôt great. 2018-19 season did happen to be one of the best I‚Äôve seen in a long time so pray to the snow gods they will give us a repeat.<//text>
<pics>None</pics><response>{'time': 1583457777972, 'text': "Hello Taylor. Thank you so much for taking the time to write such a long, informative review about Squaw Valley. We are glad that you enjoy our world-class skiing and diverse terrain here, and we appreciate you voicing your other concerns as well. Your recommendations regarding visiting Truckee or Tahoe City as part of a trip are great. As far as parking goes, we have also introduced or contributed to a number of traffic-reducing and parking initiatives such as a free shuttle service, free regional buses, carpool parking, an increased number of parking spaces, a park and ride in both Truckee and Tahoe City, better snow removal equipment, and a better guided directional flow in our parking lots. This is an important issue to us, and we will continue to improve upon it wherever possible. We appreciate that you recommended Alpine Meadows as well, which is one of Lake Tahoe's best-kept secrets. Thank you for giving practical advice to our future guests! - Liz W"}<//response>< gmap_id>

< date>
1555302723812</date>
<Review>This place was highly recommended by friends and the history here made this an attractive resort to visit. The day (a Monday) we arrived it was very easy to rent demo equipment, get tickets and take the gondola up. I did pre-purchase my ticket and rental online which made the process easier. However, I will say the website could use some small improvements for online purchasing. It was **VERY** windy that day, all the peak lifts on the West side were closed, sadly. The mountain was otherwise wide open from the gondola and to the East, and lines were pretty much non-existent. It would have been a great day to bring kids to practice.

However, what made this awesome was the great customer service. Staff were nice while we were there but more importantly, they also were kind to us after we left. Idiotically, I left my helmet, goggles, and goPro attached at the demo shop's bench. I didn't realize this until I was driving past Sacramento toward the bay to fly out the next day. I didn't catch the resort operator before they closed so rang them in the morning frantically. Lost and found didn't have it (my heart dropped), but luckily I reached the demo shop person, Mo, remembered me and helped me out. She then brought it over to the shipping department where Anthony shipped my gear to back to me on the East coast. A couple days later it showed up. I did pay for shipping getting my helmet back but that is inconsequential to getting my helmet that has been with me for over a decade and the gopro footage/memories was priceless.

To Mo and Anthony, MANY MANY THANKS! I'm definitely repping Squaw Valley on my helmet!< /Review></record></dataset><record>

< review>
I came here this winter and last winter, and it's alright! The slopes aren't too varied and the snow quality wasn't super great, but the runs are quite wide. The runs aren't too long though, and the lines are quite long. Thankfully, there are single lines though so that makes waiting a bit shorter. The parking lot is huge, and the gondola is quite good.< /review>

<username>Julia Enthoven<//username><Time>1491917059037<//Time>< Rating>

< Review>
The lift tickets are expensive, but there is so much great terrain at every level. You could ski KT-22 and the Headwall all day. Check the lift status before you head to the mountain. On a great day, be prepared to wait in lift lines in the morning. The food and post-ski options are average - we had very dry sandwiches and waited a long time for beer. My mom has had a bad experience with the ski patrol people here, so look out for your own!< /Review>

<Text>The resort/ village is awesome and beautiful! The best skiing is definitely upper mountain but lower mountain is very good too. The powder is magic! I feel there is a good mix of black turn blue trails. Then of coarse there are pure adrenaline runs and easy sliders. When everything is running lines are minimal to perfect. The weather is a tricky balance when planning a trip. High winds, avalanche control, or initial rain turn snow can snuff out a couple days. Overall we have been lucky to catch at least 2-3 good skiing days out of 4-5 day stays we have had in our three trips here (Dec '16, Mar '18, Feb '19). I was able to get refunded as an out of stater instead of a snow check. Staff is great! I know it is a little pricey but as an east coast dweller the experience is worth the splurge.<//Text><resp>{'time': 1550704347156, 'text': "Hi Nicklas, thank you for your review of Squaw Valley. <date>1496079227524<//date><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Squaw Valley is the biggest mountain around Lake Tahoe.  It is pretty far driving from South Lake (over 1 hour) but not a bad drive from Incline, Truckee, or Reno. It's gorgeous in the winter and summer. On Memorial Day annually they host a Made-in-Tahoe event with local artisans, food vendors, and live music...easily my favorite event of the year. Stunning backdrop of alpine meadows and the dramatic cliffs of squaw valley ski resort. Truly beautiful year round at Squaw Valley resort.<//text>

<userid>103306827126979493100</userid><time>1511331392032< /time>< text>
Best resort in the Lake Tahoe area, hands down. Best beginner area, best double-black terrain and best infrastructure (lifts, village, etc.) Even though it's more expensive than every other resort, you get what you pay for. With more than 4,000 skiable acres, you can spend an entire winter here and not ride every run. This place caters to everyone...but, actually, don't go here because it's already too packed.

We came up on November 20th and were surprised to find no crowds and 3+ feet of relatively fresh snow up at High Camp. Was a perfect time to bring beginners up the hill to practice turns before the holiday season begins and floods of people come up from the city and dump off their rude, entitled punk children on the beginner slopes who tend to ruin the experience for others.< /text>

Expensive ski resort, but the mountain is world class. I was not a particularly skilled snowboarder the first time I came here, but because the mountain is so large there is truly something for everyone. <UserId.>103903225066695251689< /UserId.>< user_name>
Arthur Zarins<//user_name>
< Time>
1587058834376<//Time>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<Text>Up until the 2019/2020 season, I was using the Epic pass so I could ski Northstar, Heavenly, and Kirkwood. I tried an IKON pass this season (so I could have a trip to Mammoth), and I was a little worried about having only one mountain to ski in Tahoe on the IKON pass: Squaw Valley. Even though this season was shortened due to Covid19, I was completly blown away by how amazing Squaw Valley was a ski destination.

Firstly, the chairlifts are amazing. The iconic KT-22 chair is a high-speed quad, making lines during midday nonexistant (unless there was a huge powder dump). However, the chairlifts only get better. Headwall Express and Siberia Express, the two chairs that go to the top of the mountain with advanced terrain, are both 6-seaters. In addition, Intermediate chairlifts Gold Coast Express, Shirley Express, and Far East Express are all 6-seaters too! The Beginners won‚Äôt be dissapointed either, as beginner lift Big Blue (False advertising?) is also a 6-seater! All in all, we get:

-6 express 6-seater lifts
-2 express 4-seater lifts
-9 slow chairlifts that run daily
-4 slow chairlifts that run rarely

Secondly, the advanced terrain is going to be a lot better than other areas. Like falling down chutes and being watched from several chairlifts? The Palisades are for you. Don‚Äôt like crowds? Head over to Granite Chief chair or the Silverado ski territory. Want to see the US‚Äô best chairlift and lift-served ski terrain? Head on over to KT-22 Express - it‚Äôs up there with chair 23 at Mammoth for interesting chair rides. If you go up KT-22 Express and you get scared, take a right at the top, and take Saddle, the easiest way down (called a double blue, but it‚Äôs not that hard). For those who want to spend a whole day at KT-22, Saddle Face, Olympic Lady, and Schimmelpfenning Bowl are great trails to warm up on. G.S. Bowl is also a great run, although be careful, as it‚Äôs a long way to the bottom if you fall.

Sadly, there's a character limit, so I can't get into detail on Intermediate/Beginner terrain, but it exists, is good, and is serviced with high-speed 6-seater chairlifts!

And the ski mountain is going to expand too! A California Express Gondola has been approved, and it will link Squaw Valley, Alpine Meadows, and (based on the blueprint) the backside of KT-22 (a.k.a. Troy Caldwell‚Äôs white wolf mountain) into one single ski resort! This Gondola will have 4 stations: Bottom of Squaw Valley, Top of KT-22, Bottom of KT-22 backside (the most odd and interesting one), Bottom of Alpine Meadows. I can‚Äôt wait for this gondola to be built in the future, as this plan has been going for quite some time. If you take the KT-22 chairlift to the top and go straight, you will see an unfinished KT-backside chairlift that just needs a cable and chairs on it to run. I‚Äôm confident that this chair will start running once the Gondola is built and functioning, and that this new territory will be opened up for everyone. However, this will remove the Red Dog chairlift, which will disrupt the whole East side of Squaw, as only Squaw Creek would get to the peak of Snow King, as Far East Express doesn‚Äôt go the full height. Given that the owner is replying to some of the reviews, I would like to know what‚Äôs going to happen after the California Gondola is installed, and Red Dog is removed. Will there be a Platter lift from the top of Far East Express to the top of Snow King? Will Red Dog‚Äôs base terminal simply be put higher up the mountain? Will the backside of KT-22 open up? Will the Olympic lady chair become obsolete, and be removed (it doesn‚Äôt run much already)? If the Olympic lady chair is removed, will it be relocated to Alpine Meadows or the backside of KT-22? No matter what happens, it looks like the iconic KT-22 chair will remain open, which I think we can all agree that it is more important than the Snow King area.

And that‚Äôs all I have to say about Squaw Valley!< /Text>< pics>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
There are a few things I'm not tremendously fond of with Squaw, first is the crowds, second is the lack of trees on the ski terrain, and third is how quick they are to close the ski lifts on stormy days. There's a lot that I like, such as Squaw is amazing when you catch an event or day of skiing that's not too busy. I have been fortunate to be able to attend events on days that attract smaller crowds and I have always had such a lovely time. The resort is beautiful with great food options. The pool is super awesome. The terrain is fun to ski/ride. There's something for everyone.<//text>

<review>This resort offers pretty good skiing and the views are amazing, However:
1) Even though the weather was really good today (apart from a little wind) they decided to close a part of the mountain which meant a lot of lines to the chairlifts and busy slopes. Which caused quite a few accidents.
2) They also closed a couple of runs to prepare for a ski competition a week ahead. In a couple of places they left narrow steep passage, along with the ice this felt pretty dangerous. And indeed someone eventually broke their collar bone because they ran into another person.
3) Ski pass is ridiculously expensive. And also the food. $12 for a bowl of chili? $13 for a chicken sandwich?
4) none of the chairlifts had a bar to put your skis/snowboard on so they had to hang in the air.
5) The entrance to almost all the chairlifts is downhill, so with the ice today people ended up sliding into the person in front.
6) When you get out of the chairlift you need to walk uphill before you can slide down. Who designed this?<//review>< Date>

Go to the restaurants and shops

Our goal with POW Parking is to encourage our guests to carpool to help reduce our carbon footprint and combat the traffic congestion issues we deal with daily in the Tahoe area. The paid parking option was available earlier this season to allow vehicles with fewer than 3 people to park in that carpool lot, but we eliminated the paid option earlier this season and reverted the lot back to carpool-only parking.\nThanks for asking! :-) We hope to see you again next season in one of our free or carpool lots!\nCheers,\nAnne\n\nOriginal response on 4/17:\nDear Mike,\nThank you for visiting Squaw Valley and for taking the time to leave a review. <name>Erick Wayland< /name><date>1580514028892< /date><rating>5<//rating>< text>
Beautiful resort, host to the olympics in the day. Tons of terrain to shread. Families take the Funitel to the Gold Coast base where most of the beginner terrain and a good deal of intermediate terrain sit in a beautiful bowl area with access to about 6 lifts that will entertain most all day long. High camp has food and Gold Coast along with exterior seating weather permiting. Now for the more advanced head up top on  siberia or headwall for lots of open face bowls or on backside toward granite chief for some trees and steeps. Also at the base you can hit kt22 or red dog for an  additonal load of advanced terrain. This mountain offers lots of fun for all levels, friends and family alike. Certainly lessons from noob to advanced available for riding and skiing. Weekends can be very crowded, mid week if able, rocks. Have a blast and winter it up.</text>
<Pics>None< /Pics>< Response>

<UserId.>113860995206703528376</UserId.><Name>kyle smith</Name><Time>1551493105091< /Time>< rate>
2<//rate>
<Review>Not what it used to be. It used to be an iconic resort with unbelievable terrain and a wonderful ski culture. Now it is nothing more than a holding on the books of an investment company. They don't care about skiing and they could care less about the customer experience.

I'm sure someone in the marketing department will reply to this review and say how much they care about their customers, but I can assure you they don't operate the mountain as if they do. These days they spend way more time marketing the mountain and making sure it is constantly packed (which it is) than they do making an effort to operate the mountain and open terrain. 2,3,4 days after a storm they still struggle to get areas of the mountain open and they make excuses and whine on social media like there's no tomorrow. If it snows, they shut down. If it's windy, they shut down. I can probably count on one hand the amount of days that all the lifts have been running on the same day this season. The bottom line is that they either have no idea how to run a ski area or they just don't bother to do it because it isn't profitable enough for them.

If I were ranking the mountain on the terrain, it would be a 5, the mountain is awesome. Unfortunately the people running it bring it down to 2/5 stars. It really is sad, I love Squaw with all my heart. I wish they could pull it together and run as smoothly as they did when Alex Cushing owned it.<//Review>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

<Review>I didn't get a normal experience at Squaw, but I can say that their safety and ski patrol is very solid. In a

<rate>1< /rate><review>Went on one of the best snow days of the year with the whole family.  After spending about $900 on lift tickets and ski rentals, got to top of first run and Squaw shuts down 99% of the lifts claiming too windy.

It was a little windy, but after an hour it was blue skies and they still kept all lifts closed except for one or two and lift lines were 45 minutes.  A friend called me from top of a run he hiked up to (because lifts were closed) and said it wasn't windy at all.  They kept only 2 lifts open the rest of the day and the crowds/lines were unbearable.

The previous day we didn't go because we watched the online lift reports and saw the same thing happened.  It was windy that day, but not bad.  The day we went it was nice but still they kept lifts closed.

No refunds were given either day.  After spending $500 for cabin, $900 for skis, and gas to drive up I won't be going back there again.

I've been told by long time Squaw locals that the management isn't running their finances well and that this was likely a cost cutting attempt to avoid having to pay lift ops and electricity.  They won't be renewing their season  passes next year.< /review>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

<text>A bit pricey, but really huge and amazing ski resort. One thing, though, if you don't know a bit of skiing already, this may not be the best place to learn. All the green slopes are at the top, and there's not an easy way to get all the way down the mountain. So you need to take the lifts and tram back. I wish they would make a green route all the way down.

If you can handle blue, then it's great, and lots of more challenging runs for the experts. If it's your first time skiing, maybe learn somewhere smaller first and then come here once you're confident stopping and turning.</text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

<name>Jason Gallardo< /name>< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
<rate>1<//rate>< Response>
None</Response>
< text>
While the skiing here can be great, the early season is terrible and they offer no discounts for early season.  We paid full price for 20% of the lifts open.  Additionally, the majority of the runs during December are in the shade and completely icy.  The staff seems preoccupied with catching up with their friends and smoking weed- there are exceptions, but the majority are immature and don't treat it like a job.  All in all the worst ski experience I've had in 30 years of skiing (including Colorado, Utah, New Mexico, Europe, and even back east in Massachusetts and Vermont.  I waited 2 months to post this, but after an awesome day at Bear Mountain of all places, with peaks at only 8,500, I just realized I paid twice as much for Squaw, for only half the experience.</text>
<Gmap_id>0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f</Gmap_id>< Time>
1520045902349<//Time>
</record></dataset><record>
< time>
1439091109664</time>
< GmapID>
0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f< /GmapID>
< Text>
Was here the last week in July 2015, with my wife and 13 year old daughter. We loved it!! The 1 bedroom condo was huge and clean and beautiful decorated in rustic mountain style. The kitchen was well stocked. The village area was great, a very casual and mellow atmosphere. We ate at two restaurants in the village, a Irish Pub and Fireside Pizza, both were excellent. The pizza place had live entertainment on the outside deck. We enjoyed the campfires placed around the village, and also saw a evening movie playing outdoors. Personally as the Dad on the trip, I appreciated the front desk help when asking about good places to hike and swim. The girl at the desk was patient and wrote down all the best hiking trails on a map, and her favorite beach. We did most of them, and every one was a jem! After our 4 nights stay, both my wife & daughter complimented me on choosing the Squaw Valley Resort. So, right there, a winner.

If we return to Tahoe, which is very likely as it's the most beautiful place on Earth. We will be back at Squaw Valley.< /Text>

Mina Thai<//name>
< Date>
1517093680726< /Date>
< Rating>
5</Rating>
<text>Squaw Valley is one of my favorite resorts within the Tahoe/Reno area.  Within the ten years of snowboarding,  I've been to all the resorts and still find myself visiting Squaw Valley at least once every season.  There are many qualities makes Squaw outshine all the others. I'll highlight my main reasons:

1. Everyone is friendly - from the staffs at the parking lot to the staffs high above the mountain.

2. Diverse staffs - not many people will pay attention to this,  but I do as I have older parents who are actively working bc aren't ready for retirement.  I appreciate the fact that Squaw doesn't discriminate; age, gender,  race,  etc.  You can connect with any staffs there bc of it.

3. Clean - I'm not sure about the men's restrooms, but the women's are clean.  They also have complimentary feminine products.

4. Price - if you buy your ticket online early,  you'll save at least $40. We bought ours online for $129; on day of, it was $169. The online purchase do not have expiration date and you can use them individually.

Overall,  those are my main reasons for supporting and coming back to Squaw Valley besides their multiple runs for different level - beginners to experts.<//text><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>
None<//Response>

<Time>1501351129140< /Time><rating>3< /rating>< Review>
Decent place, we stayed in a 2BR condo. Only problem was the AC. I know it's a winter resort, but if you're going to rent it in the summer, you need real AC. Their alternative is a very noisy portable unit in the family room that vents onto the patio (which makes that area hard to use due to the hot exhaust), with box fans to blow cool air into the bedrooms. I thought it was a joke until I called the front desk. Our room was 85 degrees when we checked in for those who think it doesn't get that hot. Resort overall is nice, great amenities, lots of dining options, super friendly staff.<//Review>

< text>
Squaw still ranks as my favorite general focus, all-mountain mountain in California. It's got a ton of terrain, plenty of snow, great access to fast lifts and gondolas, and a proper resort feel for apres-ski. No wonder squaw has hosted seminal moments in NA skiing history with events like the '60s Olympics and many actual olympiads. Add the growing collaboration with neighboring Alpine Meadows, and you have thousands of acres of exciting snow playground. Not to mention that Squaw keeps it's lift and season passes more affordable then the competing Northstar resort.
- 20 year fan of Squaw</text>

<user>102993759891367864707< /user><user_name>Marc David< /user_name><Time>1457217343464</Time>< Rating>
4</Rating>
< review>
After rediscovering the BayAreaSki Bus.. I started doing day trips to Squaw again. It's a nice resort, good food options, lots of runs and helpful staff.  Great place to snowboard. Especially if you are lucky enough to catch some powder off Broken Arrow.

Easy rental options and demo shops for those without their own equipment.

Expect to pay $12 for a cocktail. Roughly $12 for lunch. The lower food options are better than what you'll find in the upper mountain.

Great place for the family.< /review>

< date>
1487020244932< /date>
< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< Text>
The skiing here can be phenomenal.  Variety of terrain, elevation, snow - it's all here.  The price for such extravagance is that Squaw attracts a huge crowd.  The parking lot is huge, and it fills up, spilling over onto the access road.  On my most recent visit, the lines were long even for a Sunday (7-12 minutes, which is long for this day and age) and here at Squaw, they generally leave it to the skiers to self-regulate the lines, which *most* people do.  After all these years, I am surprised they still do not have a shuttle to get people across the treacherously icy parking lot.  Know what you are getting yourself into, and you will have a great time here!<//Text>

<name>Mama Bear<//name><Date>1438147313903< /Date><rating>3<//rating><review>It is in a great location close to Tahoe City. It's clean and visually pleasing. Our kids were excited about the water slide in the heated pool. I'm not sure what the actual temp of the pools were heated too, but it was still VERY cold. The kids couldn't stay in it very long. When Lake Tahoe's water is warmer than the pool, I wouldn't really consider those heated.
My biggest complaint which rendered my rating of three stars was the AC in the room. They have mattress covers on all the mattress that prevents them from breathing. We would turn our AC down as low as it would let us, and we would still wake up burning up. We called almost every day complaining. They offered to move us, but I went to that room first to see if it was any cooler and it wasn't. The hallways always felt amazing! I was tempted to pull my bed out there. We would lower the thermostat every night to the lowest it would go and when we woke up burning up it would be 4 degrees higher.
We just called down again to tell them the thermostat is changing from where we are setting it. A guy came into the room to look at it and advised us that these systems were just recently changed to new systems and the thermostats reset after 6-8 hrs. So, I told him when I wake up burning up its because the thermostat is changing 4 degrees higher. He pretty much was like yeah that's what it does. He said the old systems were worst, and it took them 5 yrs to finally get them replaced....as if this made me feel better about burning up at night. It is not worth any amount of money to me if I can not get a good nights sleep because I'm burning up!!!! Another weird design is that they have the air vent on the wall right next to the huge curtained window. Most Hotel rooms have them on the wall to where the air goes towards the beds where you actually sleep! Whoever designed this format was not feasibly thinking of sleeping in the room! We LOVE Lake Tahoe, but I'm ready to get a good nights sleep!</review>< pics>

<user_id>111710688776591139650</user_id>< user_name>
Francesca Pepoon</user_name>
< Resp>
None< /Resp>
< pics>
None</pics>
< review>
One of our favorite Tahoe ski resorts for its diverse terrain, excellent snow grooming, and best-in-class ski patrol. For intermediate and advanced skiers, there is a wide selection of groomed and open bowl skiing, especially if you include Alpine Meadows as part of Squaw Valley. What makes it such a great experience, though, is the active presence of ski patrol ensuring skiers and snowboarders are in control and safe. Unlike places like Northstar, it's far less likely you'll be hit from behind or run over by idiots who just want to see how fast they can go before they crash.

The village is lovely and has everything you need for a day, week, or season of winter fun.< /review>

Either pay $100 or so there or $97 for 12:30 time in. I highly suggest to buy it online for a slight bit more discount so your time would be more worth it.
Taking the gondolas up you will be able to start your adventures. There were tons of different lifts going to different part of the mountains. Sadly though there were some very FLAT areas which is very difficult for boarders so gotta learn to shimmy your body or if your new, just take off them bindings!

Lift tickets may cost over an arm and leg but the runs are quite long, but watch out for your last run around 4pm ...There is tons and tons of moguls so watch out for them and skiers!</text>

117435656289286629142</user>
<username>Romy Ilano< /username><date>1553005330332</date>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
My initial impressions were marred because at first I thought this was a skiier's resort, and damn, there are soooo many of them. But then as I became more educated I learned Jeremy Jones is here, and during good snow years a lot of the top snowboarders train here. The only thing that makes Tahoe stand out among other places in the USA is its snowboarders, and the awesome beauty of watching their creativity when you go ride. Squaw is great, but Alpine Meadows is even better, and it suffers the usual ills that plague Tahoe ski resorts: anti-density and NIMBY car driving wealthy homeowners block any sensible construction of middle class hotels, so they lose a lot of great vibes and there's way too much time spent driving in a parking lot unless you're super wealthy. There are no hostels here, but there are no hostels on any resorts in Tahoe, and on the plus side they offer a TART bus. There's just not as good a vibe when a place is stuffed with wealthy ski families and there are no options for single or working class people. Food is standard ski food, although the village is getting better, and it would be really cool to have banh mi and poke and French cheese and delicious baguettes and Indian rotis. The swimming pool is actually pretty fun and not cheesy at all, and man! during good years it's just so fun to watch the best snowboarders ride.</Text>

<UserId.>104215537366449346927</UserId.><user_name>ZN<//user_name><Time>1457219222433<//Time>< rate>
2</rate>
<text>Here is the deal with this place.  If you can take two weeks off and stay there, you'll be golden.  If you can go on a whim and find a place to stay on short notice or just drive back at the end of the day, that would work

But, if like most people, you can manage 3-4 long weekends in a season that you need to book at least a month of more in advance, and IF there is a storm that hits when you are there, you will be in Reno pulling slots.  Here is how it breaks down:

Storm starts, too warm - raining and windy. A few lower lifts may be open, but don't count on it.
Begins to cool, starts snowing - lifts closed due to wind
Snow finally abates - lifts closed due to avalanche danger, check back at noon, then check back at 1PM.  Lifts close at 4 so basically, they don't open.

Look, I get it, skiing is a sport that DEPENDS on bad weather.  Unfortunately, this resort is unable to operate (or unwilling to) unless the conditions are PERFECT.  I also understand the corporatification of skiing and that the location of Squaw puts it into a very strong wind channel.  But, over the years, this resort has been getting more and more conservative to the point where a season pass is just not worth it any more.<//text><pics>None<//pics><response>None< /response>< GmapID>
0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f<//GmapID>

< user>
111914821243435154687</user>
< Name>
Ben Matteo<//Name>
<Date>1548107872394</Date>< rate>
4</rate>
< review>
Long time passholder at Squaw & Kirkwood.  Squaw is an amazing mountain with unbelievable terrain, a legendary culture and some of the best local skiiers and riders in the world, including winter sports pioneers such as Shane McConkey, Jeremy Jones,  the MatchStick Productions crew, more Olympians than you can shake a stick at, and many, many others.  This is also one of the best spring skiing destinations on the planet. There are, however, some downsides: 1) squaw has become oppressively expensive in all dimensions.  A season pass is absolutely required if you want to ski there more than a few days a year- ticket window prices are now >$160, and forget about having someone lean to ski there- you are in for >$300/day- not conducive to bringing friends into the sport.  2) Squaw has been hit by climate change- it is increasingly frequent for squaw to get rain on its base, and (if we're lucky) snow on top.  3) the mountain is huge, which is amazing, but also means that some favorite (but less popular) lifts run very infrequently.  4) on the weekends or powder days, expect crowds, lots of crowds.  once the whole mountain opens, people disperse, but until then, expect to put in some line time.  On the plus side, if you put up with all of the above, you get to ski or ride squaw with some of the best winter athletes on the planet, and with terrain to test you at any ability level.  A final note, people can get agressive on line on a powder day.  Don't take it personally, they want to be in the snow and don't have patience for you not having your act together in front of them.  focus on the snow and it will all be okay...  This is a place for people who deeply love to ski and ride.  enjoy!<//review>
< pics>
None<//pics>

I have mixed feelings about this mountain. I found one particular run that I enjoyed the most and ended up coming back to. Beautiful views on top.. the kind that makes you want to wait before riding down.
Like many ski resorts , great cozy downtown area< /Review>

< Review>
On one of the nicest ski days of the season, the lifts had many mechanical problems.  The tram was closed (for more than just one day).  One lift was inoperable when the area opened.  Other lifts were in and out of service during the day.  It was a bit frustrating to be standing in line with little idea of when the out would be running again -- or, worse yet, stuck on a chairlift while the mechanics were at work.  One suspects that, because there were so many mechanical issues, this is a chronic situation due to substandard maintenance, rather than just an isolated bad day.< /Review>

<resp>None< /resp><userid>106778161954310243380<//userid><gmap_id>0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f< /gmap_id>< Name>
Shad Rahman</Name>
<rating>5< /rating>< pics>
None< /pics>
<date>1485784129095< /date>< Text>
Squaw Valley is almost too big for KSL to manage on stormy days.  Safety is always first, and delayed lift openings ensure avalanche controls are taken and skier/riders get fresh tracks as upper mountain sections open as the day progresses.  Best bets on fresh snow days are KT-22 on the lower mountain, Broken Arrow in mid-mountain, and usually Solitude/Shirley to Granite around mid-day.  If not windy, then head up the Siberia Express and Headwall Express for colder and drier conditions at North Bowl and The Slot.  And when the Emigrant lift is fixed ski/ride the Funnel into Shirley Lake.  A lot of Upper Mountain terrain is hard to open due to buried lifts; however, it is worth the wait.< /Text>

< Name>
Cory Lui< /Name>
< Text>
Awesome ski/snowboard experience! Parking was easy and close to the mountain which allowed us to leave our lunches in our car (and not pay money to rent a locker). Renting snowboard and boot was very professional. They had a whole assembly line going which removed the confusion of who was going to help you. Fast forward to the end of the day and returning your equipment was very easy! :)

We had a few beginners in our group but it was awesome that the green runs were not just at the bottom of the mountain. We were pleasantly surprised to find a whole green run oasis at the top of the Tram. This allowed our group to split up but not have to worry about taking a long time getting back to each other.

Definitely will come back here again :)</Text>

< Text>
The runs and snow were great.
For a first time there, they were terrible at directing us where to go to get tickets and hire equipment. We ended up queueing in the wrong shop (the inn ski shop), not squaw valley, before getting turned away. Then they gave us the wrong voucher to get ski clothes and had to call someone to switch the voucher out.
They don't rent jackets, and quickly run out of ski pants.< /Text>

< pics>

<GmapID>0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f<//GmapID>< Date>
1519331363261< /Date>
< userid>
114741650748646455554< /userid>
< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< username>
Daniel Adams</username>
< pics>
None<//pics>
< Text>
To be honest, some of the reviews of Squaw are not so hot, so I tried to keep my expectations in check. This was my wife and I's first trip to Squaw, let alone any ski area outside of the east coast. We had an absolute blast! Conditions were as good as they could be for being somewhat warm, the views and atmosphere are astounding. Traffic and parking was no problem at all because we made sure to get there an hour early to prep and catch first chair.

Some other's were upset that they weren't opening the lifts early, but it was no big deal, we were just happy to be in the mountains. Crowds were none existent for the first hour, then they set in and the longest wait was maybe 10 min, but later in the day the Funitel had no line so you could just ski right up to it.

The day was going great until I decided to do one last run while my wife rested, so I decided to take a whack at Lower Dog Leg, bad decision. Black diamonds are a little different here than on the east coast. Wound up taking a hell of a fall and breaking two bones in my leg, gear flying everywhere. Once the snow settled, a snowboarder stopped, helped me gather my gear and alert ski patrol. Took a ride down the mountain on a sled to their urgent care. Got x-rays taken, confirmed things were not great, got an air cast, crutches, and pain meds. So out trip had to end early.

That being said, everyone we interacted with on the mountain was great, employees were all pleasant, happy, smiling. Made for a great experience. Ski patrol was absolutely top notch, got me out of a hairy situation quickly and safely, did an absolute great job.

We will be back without a doubt!!</Text>

< Review>
This is one of  the most poorly managed resorts I've ever skied at.  They can't get anything with pitch open, and proximity to SF means massive lines on the lower mountain (the only open areas). They stated wind hold today and Ave danger on a day with 0 wind and every other Tahoe resort was fully open. If there is av danger four days after the last storm it's because you haven't done your job yet.

Tons and tons of intermediates everywhere. Poorly maintained, badly managed, and an extremely sour vibe at the resort from all the  locals that feel their seasons were stolen by this crap management Co. This place badly needs a change in ownership.  Have skied all over the world, will never, ever return.</Review>

< GmapID>
0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f< /GmapID>
< Text>
Good challenging terrain for expert skiers. Ownership sucks and mountain operations are terrible. Lifts like Broken Arrow and Olympic Lady almost never run. I've been skiing here for 35 years and mountain operations use to be quite good. New ownership (KSL) frequently stops or doesn't open lifts to save money. They are often short staffed. Lift lines, parking, traffic to get to the mountain are all horrible! We have nicknamed the KSL ownership "Keep Stopping Lifts" or "Keep Standing in Line". Even though they don't limit season pass sales, they won't refund your season pass if you get injured. Instead they have a terrible business practice of requiring customers to buy "insurance" to get any kind of refund if they can't ski. Talk about adding insult to injury! The only thing being insured is the profits of KSL! They are a big corporation that only cares about profits and they lack focus on customer service in what should be an enjoyable experience for all in a recreational venue.<//Text>

< user>

< Pics>

<Time>1392602350755< /Time>< review>
This review is not about the ski area (which is beautiful) but about the Squaw Kids Ski school.
If you are considering group ski lessons for a beginner child (mine is 6): run away. Run away as fast as you can. Based on my experience this place is light years away from being able (or willing) to teach young kids the joy of skiing.
I enrolled my son in an afternoon group lesson for first time skiers (price in 02/14 is $169 including gear for 2.5h of ski lessons). What my son got for this was:
20 minutes gear fitting
30 minute juice break
Approximately 30-40 minutes sitting around in the snow and about 1h of actual playing in the snow which sums up to two rides on the magic carpet, a little intro to "pizza and French fries" and, well, nothing else. This is it.
Afterwards I talked to a very friendly and professional supervisor who had nothing of any significance to add to this. It appears as if this is very much the experience that is expected. He did mention that it was a very busy day (yes, Presidents' Day weekend is crazy indeed), but from my vantage point this is *his* issue to manage (staff up more, take fewer kids, hire more competent people) but should not make a first day of skiing a "I don't think I want to do this ever again, we were only sitting around" type of experience.
Based on my experience in Washington state this is not typical for kids skiing lessons. Snoqualmie, Crystal Mt both offered much better lessons for the kids (my older son did his first steps on skis there).

So yeah, run, run fast. I hear Northstar offers a more fun environment and less frustration.</review>

108735633587622834155< /user_id>

<rate>1<//rate>< text>
I've seen a lot of complaints about the instructors and man oh man, do I agree.  I wasn't someone that paid for the lessons, but I was another person on the mountain.  I almost collided with someone that was being instructed and it was a complete accident.  This person was going straight across in front of me.  I saw him and was moving out of his way as far as possible to the left.  He kept going to the left and although I thought I had enough room to move around him, he continued to move straight across in front of me.  By the time I was closer to him, it was too late to slow down enough to avoid him.  So I started to shout to make sure he saw me, narrowly missed him and our boards touched just a smidge.  I looked behind me to make sure he was okay and that he hadn't fallen.  He hadn't.

However, he was with an instructor that actually was telling this guy to cross like that!  The instructor started yelling at me down the mountain, cursing at me!  It was a clear mishap, but the instructor was not having any of it.  The instructor bombed down the hill and caught up with me when I was taking a rest on the mountain when I found my friends and husband.  I was ready to apologize and tell him that there was no harm meant, but he was extremely condescending, talking to me as if I was some reckless teenager.  "YOU - take your earphones off.  Make sure you can hear me.  That was completely your fault."  At that point, I was angry, "no... I tried to stop and because I couldn't predict where he was going, I was having trouble.  It was an accident."  "No" he says, "that was your fault.  You were not paying attention."  "Yes I was.  I couldn't avoid him, even though I tried."  The person that was being instructed was sheepishly looking on, as if he wanted no part of this.  The instructor clearly wanted me to apologize, but because of the way he approached me and his unwillingness to understand that accidents can happen regardless of how careful one is, I was NOT going to.

I told him I was going to report him.  He said, "go ahead!  Here's my card, I hope you do report me!"

This guy completely ruined my time at Squaw and I'm not willing to go back...especially with so little snow and the ticket prices increasing.  There are far more mountains to choose from than have to deal with this crap.

He's supposed to set a good example on the mountain rather than continue a culture of anger and yelling.  Awesome job guy.  I hope you were a seasonal employee.<//text>

At Squaw Valley you can hang out  next to the fire  after you're done  in the evening  or grab dinner . Northstar is a fun place to go skiing or snowboarding, but it does not have the amount of difficult Terrain that you find at Squaw Valley. <Time>1457661718824<//Time><Rate>3</Rate>< gmapID>
0x809bd9ecf08f263d:0x30be88f09785170f<//gmapID>
<Review>8584zender hit the nail on the head; it can be very frustrating to fly in from out of town to spend a long weekend here. If it's storming then you're screwed and if it's not storming then there's no fresh snow.

I don't know if it's just poorly laid-out (how could a world-class ski resort be so crippled by wind?) or if there is just a lack of staff to get all the jobs done that need to get done to open the mountain on time but it is extremely frustrating to be there during a storm that is dumping snow by the foot that you can't ski on because the lifts won't or can't open on time or at all.

Btw, if you are skiing with beginners (or you yourself are a beginner), you may want to consider another mountain. The big area of green trails at the top of the mountain looks enticing on a trail map, but you can only ski there if the top of the mountain is open (definitely not a given). If the top of the mountain is closed due to wind or storms then there is almost no beginner terrain on the entire mountain.

It's a shame because it is a great mountain with awesome terrain that should be one of the top resorts in the country.</Review><user_id>105396854759299535398<//user_id></record>
</dataset><record>

Ben Schaeffer<//username>
<userid>111936744794426364994</userid><Date>1452169368325< /Date>< Text>
I have to admit, I like Squaw MORE than both Heavenly & Northstar. I think it does the whole "Mega-resort" thing with more understatement then either of the other two. I REALLY ‚ù§ Alpine Meadows (which is also like Kirkwood -- my other medium sized mountain favorite) and the fact that you can ski both Squaw and Alpine both in a day and mix it up is SUPER convenient for the experience. I still prefer Alpine over Squaw because I am a fan of smaller less mega-resort type places, but Squaw I actually do like VERY MUCH. More
than I expected to. This year I opted to not renew my Epic Pass to Heavenly, Northstar & Kirkwood and bought the Tahoe Super Pass to Alpine, Squaw, Sugar Bowl + Sierra At Tahoe. TOTALLY worth it! Next two trips are more Alpine/Squaw and then Sugar Bowl. I like this pass more than the Epic, because you get a whole extra mountain (4 versus 3) AND, the other offers and benefits kind of outclass the Epic Passes. However, I miss Kirkwood, so I MIGHT eventually go back to the Epic pass for a season, but I TOTALLY recommend the Tahoe Super Pass -- ABSOLUTELY WORTH IT!<//Text>
